<div class="dablink">For the film adaptation, see <a href="/wiki/Slaughterhouse-Five_(film)" title="Slaughterhouse-Five (film)">Slaughterhouse-Five (film)</a>.</div>
<p><i><b>Slaughterhouse-Five, or The Children's Crusade: A Duty-Dance With Death</b></i> (1969), by <a href="/wiki/Kurt_Vonnegut" title="Kurt Vonnegut">Kurt Vonnegut</a>, is a <a href="/wiki/Post-modern" title="Post-modern" class="mw-redirect">post-modern</a> <a href="/wiki/Anti-war" title="Anti-war">anti-war</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novel</a> dealing with a soldier's (<a href="/wiki/Billy_Pilgrim" title="Billy Pilgrim">Billy Pilgrim</a>) experiences during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a> and his journeys with <a href="/wiki/Time_travel" title="Time travel">time travel</a>.</p>
